    {
      "id": "0aabfbe2f1f79b6ead42514d22c3b02449b71f3e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-11-18 14:58:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nFrom the commit message upstream it appears we should be using __set_page_dirty_nobuffers() instead of exporting __set_page_dirty_nobuffers() again.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "55853058b977073e7ca21bf451b2e8ae4b05659b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-11-18 15:28:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nI think Patrick comments are only true for older kernels.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "d5587e32f253cb0dde56d30fb98d33443d981549",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 808,
        "name": "Shaun Tancheff",
        "email": "shaun.tancheff@hpe.com",
        "username": "stancheff"
      },
      "date": "2019-11-19 16:38:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> __set_page_dirty_nobuffers\n\nIn this case __set_page_dirty_nobuffers is being open coded to reduce lock contention, unfortunately account_page_dirtied going away breaks this open coding.\n\nPossibly this type of optimization could be moved upstream with the introduction of a set_pagevec_dirty_nobuffers()?\nfs/btrfs/extent_io.c has extent_range_redirty_for_io which could use such an optimization.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "ac3feeb6a068d8d8a89ec31877f73f2152b78752",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-11-19 17:14:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nIf we can another case besides btrfs would could justify such a change.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "e17c20ef317c55c71163f7b9cace1c558afa3713",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 808,
        "name": "Shaun Tancheff",
        "email": "shaun.tancheff@hpe.com",
        "username": "stancheff"
      },
      "date": "2019-11-19 19:28:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> If we can another case besides btrfs would could justify such a change.\n\nThese two also operate on multiple pages and could be refactored to use such an 'set_pagevec_dirty_nobuffers()' \n\nfs/cifs/cifssmb.c - cifs_writev_complete\nfs/nilfs2/page.c - nilfs_copy_dirty_pages",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "c47dd3620dda88cd5721ffb76f4b051969f29015",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2019-11-19 22:50:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nfs/ceph/file.c: put_bvecs is similar, though it want to lock each individual page, so it could be a lot slower.\nIn the common case, those pages probably aren't locked, so it could still benefit from batching.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
